        "difficultyTier": "advanced",
        "hiddenInfo": "The command structure of the Ironmarch Bunker Complex has been systematically corrupted over the past five years, with senior officers operating a lucrative smuggling operation that sells military supplies to both Aurelion merchants and Zerathis agents. Weapons, provisions, medical supplies, and even intelligence documents disappear from inventory through falsified records, then resurface in black markets across the border. The operation is protected by a network of bribed guards, complicit quartermasters, and intimidated junior officers who fear career destructionor worseif they speak out. A journalist from the Lumeris Free Press, investigative reporter Kara Venn, has been attempting to expose the corruption for months, but her inquiries are systematically stonewalled: interviews are canceled, documents go missing, and she's repeatedly escorted off-base by armed guards citing 'security concerns.' Commander Theron Blackwood, the bunker's senior officer, personally oversees the operation while maintaining an impeccable public reputation as a dedicated defender of the Republic. The smuggling has weakened defensive readiness in subtle but significant waysammunition stockpiles are lower than records indicate, emergency provisions have been replaced with inferior substitutes, and some magitech defense systems lack critical components sold to the highest bidder. Border Wardens stationed at the complex are divided: some participate willingly in the profits, others suspect wrongdoing but lack evidence or courage to act, and a few have quietly begun gathering proof while fearing discovery. The operation has created strange alliancesAurelion merchants coordinate with Zerathis intelligence agents through neutral intermediaries, both sides profiting while the Republic's border defense slowly hollows from within. Most disturbing is evidence suggesting the corruption extends beyond Ironmarch, with similar operations at other defensive positions along the line, all coordinated through encrypted communications that reference only 'the Network.' If exposed, the scandal could devastate public trust in the Border Wardens and leave the Ironmarch Line vulnerable during the very crisis it was built to prevent.",
