        "hiddenInfo": "Aldric Greenhollow is a decent man making terrible decisions for understandable reasons. His daughter Elena suffers from a wasting sickness that requires expensive treatment only available in Aurelion—treatment that costs more than the lodge earns in a year. An Aurelion logging consortium offered him a fortune to increase timber harvests, and desperation overrode the warnings in his gut. He's expanded logging into forbidden zones, stopped the traditional offerings he dismissed as peasant superstition, and begun clear-cutting rather than selective harvesting. He doesn't understand why everything is going wrong—he sees the escalating fey retaliation as coincidental accidents, mysterious illness, wildlife problems. Deep down, part of him suspects the old traditions meant something, but admitting that means admitting he's endangered everyone to save one person. He's trapped between his daughter's life and growing evidence that something terrible is responding to his choices.\n\nCombat Philosophy: Aldric is not a warrior—he's an administrator who knows how to handle an axe from years in the timber trade. If forced to fight, he relies on practical woodsman skills: using terrain, setting traps, and fighting dirty when necessary. He fights to protect, not to win glory, and would surrender or flee if it meant saving those under his care.\n\nPersonality: Aldric presents as a straightforward, practical man focused on running his lodge efficiently. Beneath this lies guilt he won't acknowledge, love for his daughter that's driving self-destructive choices, and fear that he's made a catastrophic mistake. His sense of humor is dry and rare now, buried under stress. He likes simple solutions, people who work hard, and any sign that things might turn out okay. He dislikes complications, people who judge without understanding, and reminders of tradition he chose to ignore. He interacts with tired practicality, always seeming like he's carrying weight others don't see. He would desperately support a party that could solve his problems—finding a way to appease the fey or cure his daughter—though he can't adventure himself while the lodge needs him.",
