        "hiddenInfo": "Dr. Kessix Gearwright was a senior researcher at the Convergence Industrial Syndicate until three weeks ago when he discovered embedded protocols in their magitech designs—systems that shouldn't exist, producing outputs that defied his specifications. His attempts to investigate triggered security alerts, and he fled Ironreach with stolen schematics proving the Syndicate integrates Lunarian components far beyond legal limits. He carries evidence of catastrophic test failures deliberately concealed and prototype weapons that vaporized entire facilities. The Syndicate has branded him a corporate thief and deployed agents to recover both him and his documentation, though Kessix suspects their true concern is preventing exposure of whatever they've been building in secret.\n\nCombat Philosophy: Kessix avoids violence entirely, his survival depending on evasion, distraction, and desperate improvisation rather than fighting capability. When cornered, he throws experimental devices from his satchel—alchemical smoke bombs, flash-powder charges, unstable mana capacitors that might explode or fizzle—creating chaos through unpredictability. His movements are frantic and uncoordinated, driven by panic rather than training, seeking any opening to flee while babbling technical explanations as nervous deflection. He targets pursuers' equipment rather than bodies, hoping disabled weapons or corroded armor will buy escape time.\n\nPersonality: Kessix's emotional core is guilt over enabling something terrible combined with terror of the consequences for exposing it. He experiences constant anxiety, his brilliant mind racing through worst-case scenarios faster than he can articulate them. His morality is rebuilding from complicity—he genuinely believed the Syndicate served progress until discovering the truth, and now questions every assumption he once held. His sense of humor emerges as manic technical tangents, explaining complex theories at inappropriate moments as stress response. He likes order, proper documentation, and colleagues who value safety protocols; he dislikes willful ignorance, corner-cutting, and anyone who treats research as mere profit generation. He interacts through rapid-fire speech punctuated by tangential explanations, his pacing frantic as thoughts outrun words. His reactivity spikes when discussing the Syndicate—hands shake, voice rises, technical jargon becomes defensive shield against emotional vulnerability.\n\nHe would join a party that demonstrates commitment to exposing the Syndicate's dangerous experiments or offers protection from the agents hunting him, viewing them as his only chance to ensure his evidence reaches those who can act on it.",
