        "hiddenInfo": "Nettle is the War-Leader of the Thornheart Clan, a title that sounds impressive until you remember he commands perhaps forty fairies armed with thorns and bad attitudes. He wasn't always this bitter—sixty years ago, he watched humans burn the Verdant Reaches grove to clear farmland, killing three hundred fairies including his entire original clan. He alone survived by hiding in a groundhog burrow while his family burned. He joined the Thornhearts as a refugee and has spent six decades preparing to ensure it never happens again. His plan to sabotage the magitech facility isn't born from cruelty but grim calculus: the workers number perhaps fifty, his people number two hundred, and if the blight isn't stopped soon, all two hundred will die slowly as their magic fails. He's not wrong about the math. He's not wrong that humans rarely help without profit motive. He's not wrong that the Moonpetals' diplomatic approach has failed for two years. What he refuses to see is that his attack will prove humans right to fear fairies, justifying the retaliation that destroyed the Verdant Reaches. He's become the monster humans already believed him to be.\n\nCombat Philosophy: Nettle fights like a wasp—fast, vicious, and willing to die if it means hurting his enemy. He wields a thorn-spine as a spear with surprising skill, targeting eyes, ears, and other vulnerable points on larger opponents. He coordinates Thornheart warriors in swarm tactics, dozens of fairies attacking simultaneously from all angles before vanishing into foliage. His specialty is sabotage: weakening structures, contaminating food, leading enemies into prepared traps. Against overwhelming force, he retreats to fight another day, because dead fairies can't protect the grove.\n\nPersonality: Nettle presents cold hostility to outsiders, his anger a wall preventing anyone from reaching the grief underneath. He speaks in clipped, bitter sentences and expects betrayal from every interaction. His humor is dark and cutting, mocking Pimli's optimism while secretly hoping she's right. He likes thorns, rain, watching humans trip over roots he arranged, and quiet moments when he can pretend everything is fine. He dislikes fire, loud noises, humans, and being reminded of what he's lost. He interacts through suspicion and testing—he'll insult potential allies, expecting them to prove his cynicism correct. Those who respond with patience rather than anger confuse him deeply. If someone earns his trust, his loyalty is absolute.\n\nHe would join a party that proves itself by concrete action against the facility—not promises, not diplomacy, but visible results that protect his people, even if those results don't involve the violence he planned.",
