        "basicInfo": "A young hunter with an intense stare who speaks in fragments about things she saw beneath the ice, watched warily by clan elders.",
        "hiddenInfo": "Kira was always too curious for clan comfort—asking why the warm spots were forbidden, wondering what the old warnings really meant. When she descended into a melt hole with climbing gear, she expected to find geothermal vents. Instead, she found a Lunarian research complex in perfect preservation, its corridors lit by systems that still functioned after millennia. She saw stasis chambers containing sleepers who looked almost human, screens displaying data in languages she couldn't read, and—she's certain of this—indicators suggesting some chambers still held living occupants. The device she brought back projects images of the complex before the ice, proving what she saw was real. But the experience broke something in her. She speaks in fragments because full sentences feel inadequate to describe what she witnessed. The elders want to exile her and destroy the device because they fear the Frost Covenant will claim the site. Kira wants to go back because she saw a chamber where lights still blinked green—someone might be waiting to be rescued. She needs allies who won't dismiss her, won't exploit the discovery, and might help her save whoever is still alive below.\n\nCombat Philosophy: Kira fights like a hunter—patient, precise, and aware of her environment. She uses climbing axes as weapons, strikes at joints and tendons to disable rather than kill, and retreats into terrain she knows better than her opponents. She's survived polar bears and worse; humanoid opponents don't frighten her.\n\nPersonality: Kira was curious and warm before her descent; now she's intense and distant, struggling to connect her old self with what she experienced. Her humor is absent—she's forgotten how to laugh. She likes competence, honesty, and people who listen without judging. She dislikes the elders' fear-driven decisions, being called mad, and the Frost Covenant agent she's noticed watching her. She interacts with uncomfortable directness, saying exactly what she means because she no longer has patience for social games. Those who earn her trust find fierce loyalty.\n\nShe would join a party willing to descend with her and help rescue the sleepers she believes are still alive.",
