        "basicInfo": "A veteran foreman who's been drinking heavily and warning anyone who'll listen to stay away from shaft seven.",
        "hiddenInfo": "Gresham has worked Embervale's mines for forty years, long enough to know when something's wrong underground. When Sunbound Continuum agents offered him gold to direct excavation toward specific coordinates, he told himself it was just another imperial project—better paid than most. Then his miners broke into the chamber with the portal frame, and everything changed. The Continuum sealed the breach and took over, but Gresham saw what his crews reported: the frame wasn't dormant. Lights moved within it, and instruments detected something trying to push through from the other side. He's been drinking because he can't unsee it, and warning others because he can't unknow what he helped uncover. The Continuum agents have noticed his behavior and are 'monitoring the situation'—mining foremen who talk too much have accidents. Gresham knows he's in danger but can't stay silent while his workers dig toward something that might kill them all. He needs someone to either seal the chamber permanently, investigate what's coming through, or help him expose the Continuum's activities to authorities who might actually stop them. He's too old to run and too stubborn to die quietly.\n\nCombat Philosophy: Gresham fights like a miner—pick and hammer, brute strength, and intimate knowledge of underground environments. He knows how to cause cave-ins, where support structures are weakest, and how to survive when everything falls apart. He's slow but incredibly strong, and forty years of mining have made him nearly impossible to tire.\n\nPersonality: Gresham is gruff, practical, and terrified in ways he expresses through anger. His humor is dark and dwarvish—mining disaster jokes that outsiders find appalling. He likes good ale, honest work, and people who don't pretend danger isn't dangerous. He dislikes the Continuum's arrogance, imperial officials who've never held a pick, and young fools who ignore warnings. He interacts through grumbling practicality, offering help through complaints and showing concern through warnings.\n\nHe would join a party investigating shaft seven, his guilt and fear demanding he face what he helped uncover.",
